<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-006-177 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 522 400</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  Nov 27 1991 pA3(W) pA3(E) 18 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM plans $3 billion charge and about 20,000 job cuts; revampingplan will make units more independent, may lead to divestitures.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Carroll, Paul B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM announces that it will take a $3 billion charge that willindicate a loss for the 4th qtr 1991 but will save $1 billion in1992 and $2 billion in 1993.andP;  The $3 billion charge will coverapproximately 20,000 job cuts and effect a 'redefinition' of itsorganization.andP;  Basically, the reorganization will give moreautonomy to its divisions and could lead to divestitures.andO;Corporate headquarters will assume a more limited role, similar toa holding company.andP;  While the restructuring of business units willbe done gradually, each unit will produce its own financialstatement by the end of 1991.andP;  IBM officials say that two-thirdsof the 20,000 job cuts will be in the US while the rest will comemostly from Europe.andP;  IBM has been taking restructuring chargessince 1985.andP;  In the 1st qtr 1991, it took a $2.26 billion chargefor an accounting change.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Management).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     ManagementLossesFinancial ReportBusiness PlanningPersonnel ManagementReorganization.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>